===Etymology===
From Middle English {{m|enm|behemoth|behemoth, bemoth}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}}, from {{etyl|he|en}} {{m|he|בהמות|tr=bəhēmōth}}. The Hebrew word is either:
* an intensive plural of {{m|he|בהמה||tr=bəhēmāh|beast}}, from {{etyl|sem-pro|en}} (compare Ethiopic {{m|gez|||tr=bəhma|dumb, speechless}}, Arabic {{m|ar|||tr=ʼabham|animal}} (declined as ''bahma(t)'', ''bahīma(t)'')), or
* a borrowing of {{etyl|egy|en}} {{m|egy|||tr=p-ehe-mau|hippopotamus|lit=water-ox}}.

